nfiltrate","Intestinal metaplasia with goblet cells","Keratin pearls","Squamous epithelium"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus is characterised by the replacement of normal stratified squamous epithelium with metaplastic columnar epithelium. The key diagnostic feature is the presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintestinal metaplasia with goblet cells\u003C/strong\u003E. While \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratin pearls\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of squamous cell differentiation, they are not seen in Barrett\u0027s oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einflammatory infiltrate\u003C/strong\u003E may be present but is not diagnostic. Normal \u003Cstrong\u003Esquamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E is replaced in this condition, so its presence would argue against the diagnosis. While \u003Cstrong\u003Edysplastic changes\u003C/strong\u003E may develop in Barrett\u0027s oesophagus, they are not required for diagnosis and represent a more advanced stage of disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is characterised by intestinal metaplasia with goblet cells replacing normal squamous epithelium.","Histological diagnosis of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus requires the presence of goblet cells on biopsy."],"references":["Stawinski PM, Dziadkowiec KN, Kuo LA, Echavarria J, Saligram S. Barrett\u0027s Esophagus: An Updated Review. Diagnostics (Basel). 2023 Jan 16;13(2):321. doi: 10.3390/diagnostics13020321. PMID: 36673131; PMCID: PMC9858189.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51420"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"152